issue.title: WebUI: Add security headers to all responses

labels.name: area/UI
labels.description: Improvements or additions to UI

issue.body:
Added security middleware to prevent clickjacking and MIME type sniffing attacks by implementing X-Frame-Options and X-Content-Type-Options headers.

## Security Benefits
- **X-Frame-Options**: Prevents clickjacking attacks by controlling iframe embedding
- **X-Content-Type-Options**: Prevents MIME type sniffing vulnerabilities

  • #1570 a7c0c88 Thanks @​ItsNickBarry! - When using --diff-filter with the D option to include deleted staged files, lint-staged no longer tries to stage the deleted files, unless they're no longer deleted. Previously this caused an error from git add like fatal: pathspec 'deleted-file' did not match any files.

  • 38f942e Thanks @​iiroj! - Removed an extraneous log entry that printed shouldHidePArtiallyStagedFiles to console output.

v16.1.1

Patch Changes

  • #1565 3686977 Thanks @​iiroj! - Lint-staged now explicitly warns about potential data loss when using --no-stash.

  • #1571 02299a9 Thanks @​iiroj! - Function tasks (introduced in v16.0.0) only receive the staged files matching the configured glob, instead of all staged files.

  • #1563 bc61c74 Thanks @​iiroj! - This version fixes incorrect behavior where unstaged changes were committed when using the --no-stash option. This happened because --no-stash implied --no-hide-partially-staged, meaning unstaged changes to files which also had other staged changes were added to the commit by lint-staged; this is no longer the case.

    The previous (incorrect) behavior can still be achieved by using both options --no-stash --no-hide-partially-staged at the same time.

v16.1.0

Minor Changes

  • #1536 e729daa Thanks @​iiroj! - A new flag --no-revert has been introduced for when task modifications should be applied to the index before aborting the commit in case of errors. By default, lint-staged will clear all task modifications and revert to the original state.

  • #1550 b27fa3f Thanks @​iiroj! - Lint-staged now ignores symlinks and leaves them out from the list of staged files.

commits.message:
(#142) fix: ensure flags are not treated as paths in command parsing

- Updated the command parsing logic in TropsMain to correctly handle flags (e.g., -ar) by appending them to the result arguments without treating them as paths.
- Added a new test to verify that flags remain intact during command execution, ensuring proper functionality in the Trops CLI.

test: update logfile path assertion to be more flexible

- Modified the test_log_save function to assert that the logfile path ends with 'trops.log' instead of checking for an exact match. This change accommodates variations in the default path on different environments, such as CI or macOS, ensuring the test remains valid across setups.

test: ensure temporary files exist for TropsView tests

- Added code to create temporary files in the test_view.py file to ensure that the TropsView class can pass its file existence checks during tests. This change addresses potential failures in the tests due to missing files, enhancing test reliability.

refactor: simplify git command execution in TropsGetKm

- Replaced the use of TropsMain for git command execution with a direct call to subprocess.run, streamlining the process and reducing dependencies.
- Updated the corresponding test to reflect changes in command invocation, ensuring that the tests accurately capture subprocess calls instead of TropsMain interactions.

feat: add file filtering functionality to TropsView

- Implemented a filter input in the sidebar to allow users to search for files dynamically.
- Each file list item now includes data attributes for improved filtering logic.
- Added JavaScript functions to handle filtering and opening the first matching file, enhancing user experience and accessibility.
- Updated the sidebar layout with additional styling for the filter input and metadata display.

(#148) feat: add joinkm command for merging markdown tables

- Introduced a new command `joinkm` to join multiple KM markdown tables into a single, time-sorted table.
- Implemented input validation to ensure at least one input file and an output path are provided.
- Added functionality to read, parse, and sort rows from the input files, handling markdown table formats.
- Included an option to append to the output file instead of overwriting.
- Created corresponding tests to validate the command's functionality and ensure correct merging and sorting of input files.

(#148) test: update user@host in test_joinkm.py to reflect new host naming convention

- Modified the user@host entries in the test_joinkm.py file to replace 'icep01' with 'myhost01' for consistency with the updated host naming convention.
- Ensured that the test cases remain valid and reflect the current environment setup.

(#149) refactor: update Trops class hierarchy to use TropsBase and TropsCLI

- Replaced instances of the Trops class with TropsBase in TropsCapCmd, TropsFile, TropsInit, and TropsRepo to establish a clearer base class structure.
- Updated TropsMain references to TropsCLI in various command implementations (TropsKoumyo, TropsLog, TropsView) to reflect the new command structure.
- Ensured backward compatibility by exporting old class names for seamless transition.
- Adjusted tests to accommodate the new class structure, ensuring all functionalities remain intact.

(#150) feat: introduce TropsError exception for improved error handling

- Added a new custom exception class, TropsError, to handle errors related to Trops operations more gracefully.
- Replaced print statements and exit calls with raises of TropsError in various methods to ensure consistent error handling and allow for better control of program flow.
- This change enhances the robustness of the code by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled appropriately, rather than terminating the program abruptly.

(#150) refactor: replace SystemExit with TropsError for environment variable checks

- Updated the TropsCapCmd class to raise TropsError instead of SystemExit when the TROPS_DIR environment variable is not set or when the specified TROPS_ENV is missing in the configuration. This change enhances error handling by allowing exceptions to be caught and managed more gracefully within the application flow.
- Adjusted corresponding tests to expect TropsError instead of SystemExit, ensuring consistency in error handling across the codebase.

(#150) refactor: replace SystemExit with TropsError for improved error handling in TropsEnv

- Updated the TropsEnv class to raise TropsError instead of SystemExit for various error conditions, including unsupported arguments, missing environment variables, and invalid environment names. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow.
- Adjusted corresponding tests to expect TropsError instead of SystemExit, ensuring consistency in error handling across the codebase.

(#150) fix: enhance error handling in main function with TropsError

- Wrapped the main function's argument handling in a try-except block to catch TropsError exceptions. This change allows for graceful error reporting to stderr and prevents abrupt program termination, aligning with the recent improvements in error management across the codebase.
- This update ensures that any errors raised during argument processing are handled consistently, enhancing the robustness of the application.

(#150) refactor: replace print statements with TropsError in TropsFile for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsFile class to raise TropsError instead of using print statements and exit calls for unsupported arguments and invalid directory errors. This change aligns with the recent enhancements in error management across the codebase, allowing for more graceful error handling and consistent application flow.

(#150) refactor: replace print statements with TropsError in TropsGetKm for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsGetKm class to raise TropsError instead of using print statements and exit calls for various error conditions, including unsupported arguments, missing environment variables, and invalid configuration paths. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow.
- Adjusted the corresponding test to expect TropsError instead of SystemExit, ensuring consistency in error handling across the codebase.

(#150) refactor: replace print statements with TropsError in TropsInit for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsInit class to raise TropsError instead of using print statements and exit calls for unsupported arguments and invalid shell types. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow.
- Adjusted the corresponding test to expect TropsError instead of SystemExit, ensuring consistency in error handling across the codebase.

(#150) refactor: replace print statements with TropsError in TropsJoinKm for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsJoinKm class to raise TropsError instead of using print statements and exit calls for unsupported arguments, missing input files, and sorting errors. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow, ensuring consistency with recent improvements across the codebase.

(#150) refactor: replace print statements with TropsError in TropsKoumyo for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsKoumyo class to raise TropsError instead of using print statements and exit calls for unsupported arguments, missing headers, and tag validation errors. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow, ensuring consistency with recent improvements across the codebase.

(#150) refactor: replace print statement with TropsError in TropsLog for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsLog class to raise TropsError instead of using a print statement and exit call when no tags are set. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow, ensuring consistency with recent improvements across the codebase.

(#150) refactor: replace print statements with TropsError in TropsRepo for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsRepo class to raise TropsError instead of using print statements and exit calls for unsupported arguments and git command failures. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow, ensuring consistency with recent improvements across the codebase.

(#150) refactor: replace print statements with TropsError in TropsView for improved error handling

- Updated the TropsView class to raise TropsError instead of using print statements and exit calls for unsupported arguments, missing file paths, and directory/file validation errors. This change enhances error management by allowing exceptions to be caught and handled more gracefully within the application flow, ensuring consistency with recent improvements across the codebase.

pull_request.body: ## 개요 - 부스 목록 조회 API 구현 - 부스 세부 목록 조회 API 구현 - 부스 조회시 메뉴 목록도 조회 구현 - close #35 ## 설명 - `GET` `http://localhost:8080/api/festival/booth` : 모든 부스 조회 (페이징 단위) - `GET` `http://localhost:8080/api/festival/booth/{boothName}` : 부스 이름으로 공연 정보 조회 - `GET` `http://localhost:8080/api/festival/{boothName}/menus` : 부스 이름을 요청하면 메뉴목록 정보 제공 - BoothMenuDevSeeder : 후에 데이터 삽입시 사용할 코드파일 ## API요청 메시지 ### 성공 ### 실패 - 부스는 있는데 메뉴가 없으면 메뉴는 빈 리스트를 반환함 ### 📌 수정 및 변경(코드) - [x] 버그 수정 - [x] 코드 리팩토링 ### 📌 구조 변경 - [x] 파일 혹은 폴더명 수정 - [x] 파일 혹은 폴더 삭제 ### 📌 문서 작성 및 수정 - [x] 문서 수정 : 마지막 커밋 메시지에 refactor: 명시x -> chore로 빈 커밋내용 올림 --- ## 🔥 PR Checklist **리뷰어**를 위해, PR이 다음 요구 사항을 충족하는지 확인하세요. - [x] 리뷰어 설정을 했나요? - [x] 커밋 메시지, 코드 컨벤션에 맞게 작성했나요? - [x] 변경 사항에 대한 테스트를 했습니다. - [x] 🔥 병합 위치가 올바른 브랜치인지 확인하셨나요? - [x] 진짜 했나요?

issue.title: Fix group_by to_struct panic on invalid type
issue.body: Propagate schema inference errors as `PolarsResult` to prevent panics in `group_by` and other contexts. Previously, operations like `arr.to_struct()` or `name.prefix_fields()` applied to incompatible data types within a `group_by` context would cause a panic (e.g., `expect("should be resolved")`). This change modifies schema inference functions to return a `PolarsResult` and propagates errors, ensuring that such type mismatches result in a proper `InvalidOperationError` instead of a crash. ---

issue.title: Daily pending incident report broadcast
issue.body: Ensures system-generated incident tables are correctly formatted and displayed as the latest entry in chat history. Previously, these tables were saved as plain text, leading to incorrect rendering and duplicate entries in the chat history. This PR introduces a `system` flag to the chat schema, updates the cron job to clean up old table messages, and modifies the history endpoint to return only the latest, properly formatted HTML table. ---

performed_via_github_app.description:
Publish incredibly high performance websites and applications right from GitHub. The Netlify platform connects your repositories to an all-in-one workflow for global CDN deployment, continuous integration, and automatic (and free) HTTPS. Each time you commit changes, Netlify builds your site, prerenders markup, and optimizes assets on dedicated build infrastructure. Easily create an entirely automated workflows for your web applications

## Features

### Push your site live, directly from GitHub
Deploy your site to an ultra-redundant global CDN that’s purpose built for serving pages and assets quickly and consistently.

### Automate deployment
Netlify’s built-in Continuous Deployment automatically runs your build commands and deploys the result whenever you push to your Git repository.

### Add a custom domain
Purchase domains and manage DNS zones and records right inside of Netlify.

### HTTPS is automatic
Your site will automatically be secured with a free TLS certificate from Let’s Encrypt.

### Deploy Previews
Netlify’s Deploy Previews streamlined your workflow by giving you a unique, permanent URL to check what your changes will be like in production whenever you submit a pull request.

### And a lot more!
Netlify includes solutions for forms, identity, and even custom functions powered by AWS Lambda. And all this functionality can be configured directly in your repo.
